description: DC Thomson annuals featuring the working class Broon (Brown) family of Glebe Street, Aughentogle, created by Robert Duncan Low and Dudley Watkins for the Sunday Post newspaper's Fun Section in 1936. The first annual came out in 1939 (catalogued as 1940), and alternated with Low and Watkins' Oor Wullie thereafter, with Wullie annuals on even years and Broons on odd. The second Broons Annual came out in 1941, but wartime paper shortages forced DC Thomson to skip producing Broons Annuals in 1943 or 1945. The Annuals resumed in 1947, and have come out every two years since.
name: The Broons

description:
Red Robin

Starring: Tim Drake as Red Robin.

Red Robin follows Tim Drake's journey to prove that Batman, Bruce Wayne, is alive. Tim dons the mantle of Red Robin after Dick becomes Batman and chooses Damian Wayne as his Robin. So Tim travels around the world to find clues and relics from long ago. Tim ends up fighting, and later teaming up with, the League of Assassins. He begins to work with Ra's al Ghul and follows the leads that he gives him. The first twelve issues focus on that and then begin to show Tim working in Gotham.

Tim arrives back in Gotham and reunites with Superboy, Batgirl and then later the new Dynamic Duo. Tim has more trouble on his hands when Tommy Elliot, who still looks like Bruce Wayne after the events of Heart of Hush, tries to take over Wayne Enterprises. Tim finds out that Ra's put him up to this and they have a climatic fight.

The series then has Tim trying to figure out what he is going to do, where he is going to operate out of, and who to work with. Tim makes his own hit list and begins hunting down villains. Damian finds a screen of heroes to watch underneath the villain screen and he's on it. They have a fight while Dick is on a mission with the Justice League whom comes back during the fight and puts a stop to it. Currently, Tim has been following leads on the Unternet and reconnecting with the Teen Titans. 7 Days of Death has Tim across the world learning of a secret tournament filled of assassination attempts.

Red Robin will not continue with DC's relaunch and will end with issue #26 but Tim's adventures will continue in Teen Titans #1.

Collected Editions

  • Vol. 1: The Grail (#1-5)
  • Vol. 2: Collision (#6-12, Batgirl #8)
  • Vol. 3: The Hit List (#13-17)
  • Vol. 4: 7 Days of Death (#18-21, #23-26, Teen Titans #92)
name: Red Robin

description:
This was a 36 page promotional book that was supposed to be given out to movie theatres in April ,1939. Plans to distribute the comic never materialized because the series was deemed to be unsuccessful. The comic was found in the office of the departed publisher of the comic, and was sort of a hype when it was first discovered in the late 1970's.

This was because the comic featured the first appearance of Bill Everett's legendary creation, Prince Namor the Sub-Mariner in an eight page black and white story. Six months before Marvel Comics #1, (the comic people believed Namor first appeared in up until then). The comic is extremely rare, with only 6 known copy's existing.

Three more comic covers where found for Motion Picture Funnies Weekly, issue 2,3 and 4, but these where never made into a real comic book. Making number 1 the only 'real' whole comic in the series and one of the rarest comics in history.
name: Motion Picture Funnies Weekly

description:
The short lived Green Publishing Company got their start late in the Golden-Age, and their output consisted almost entirely of reprinted material from other companies, publishing items DC no longer wanted in Atomic Comics, and for Roly-Poly Comics reprinting back page also-rans from MLJ (Archie) Comics such as Señor Banana, Steel Sterling, Chimpy, Red Rube, the Applejack Twins, and the Black Hood.

It should also be noted that the numbering on Roly-Poly was odd, starting at # 1 it then skipped to # 6 for the second issue, skipped #’s 7 - 9, published 10 - 12, jumped over 13 and ended with it’s sixth and seventh issues as #’s 14 and 15.

The Covers almost never had anything to do with what appeared on the inside of the comic.
name: Roly-Poly Comics

description:
Flippy and Flop and Sam the dog first appearing in 3 also ran cartoons from Screen Gems and engaged in your basic cat chases bird, dog stops cat from eating bird, mayhem ensues sort of thing.

That would have been it for them but after the war as the market for superheroes started to die out DC decided to get in on comics about licensed cartoon characters.

Unfortunately for them by then all the famous cartoon characters had been licensed out to other publishers, so they took on a set of Screen Gems’ cartoon characters that had appeared in only a few less than successful toons. These included Fox & Crow, Tito and His Burrito, and Flippy, Flop and Sam, only DC changed the birds name to Flippity, and left the dog’s name off the title.

Their success at DC would be more pronounced than is had been on the screen.

They shared their comic with the even less original team of chesse loving mice Twiddle & Twaddle.
name: Flippity & Flop
